ICF

International Climate Finance (ICF) is Official Development Assistance (ODA) from the UK to support developing countries to reduce poverty and respond to the challenges caused by climate change and environmental degradation. These investments help developing countries to:

adapt and build resilience to the current and future effects of climate change

pursue low-carbon development

support sustainable management of natural resources

increase access to clean energy

reduce deforestation

Developed countries have jointly committed to mobilising $100 billion dollars a year in climate finance a year by 2020, to support developing countries to adapt to and mitigate the impacts of climate change1. This target is expected to be reached by 2023. However, the IPCC estimates that between $1.6 trillion to $3.8 trillion will be needed each year to 2050 for the world to transition to a low-carbon future and to avoid warming beyond 1.5C.

The UK has committed to spending 11.6 billion of ICF between financial years 2021/22 to 2025/26, with 3 billion of this to be invested in climate change solutions that protect, restore and sustainably manage nature. This budget represents a doubling of the UKs previous ICF commitment of 5.8 billion between 2016/17-2020/21. Previously, 3.8 billion was spent from 2011/12-2015/16.

The ICF portfolio is delivered jointly across three UK Government Departments: the Foreign Commonwealth & Development Office (FCDO); the Department for Energy Security and Net Zero (DESNZ formerly the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy); and the Department for Environment, Food & Rural Affairs (Defra).


Climate change

The UN has warned that the world is on the brink of a climate catastrophe, and the window to avert it is closing rapidly2. In 2022, the global mean temperature was approximately 1.13C above the pre-industrial level, making it one of the warmest years on record. To limit warning to 1.5C, as set out in the Paris Agreement, requires a 43% decrease in global greenhouse gas emissions by 2030, and net zero by 2050.

The latest assessment from the International Panel on Climate Change sets out how human-induced climate change is already having devastating impacts globally, and yet greenhouse gas emissions have continued to rise between 2020-20193. The report emphasises the interdependence of climate, ecosystems and biodiversity, and human society, and the need for an integrated approach across these areas to solve the challenges we face. Every year the window for action gets smaller, while the risks we face become more complex and dangerous. The impacts of climate changes extend across the Sustainable Development Goals4, with increased extreme weather events already driving mass mortalities in plant and animal species, and millions of people increasingly exposed to food and water insecurity.

While the IPCC assessment stressed the severity of the situation, it also outlines how it is still possible to achieve the necessary emissions reductions to keep global warming to 1.5C5, while every 0.1C of heating we avoid will improve our chances of limiting climate catastrophe. Major transitions will be required in the energy sector to reduce our dependence on fossil fuels, alongside improvements in urban design and transport to reduce energy consumption. More efficient use and recycling of resources in industry and improvements in agriculture and land use will also be key areas for progress, helping to reduce greenhouse gas emissions while providing co-benefits for nature. Significant progress was made at the United Nations Climate Change Conference (COP26), hosted by the UK in 2021. The Glasgow Climate Pact was agreed, which set out ambitious commitments to ramp up action on climate change6. These include phasing down coal and ending fossil fuel subsidies for the first time, over 90% of the global economy now covered by net zero pledges, and increased support to developing countries, including at least doubling adaptation finance to $40bn a year by 2025. If countries live up to the promises made at Glasgow, warming could be limited to below 2C, but increased action is needed to keep us to the lower 1.5C ceiling set out in the Paris Agreement7. The UK will work closely with the incoming COP27 presidency, Egypt, to push for scaling up commitments in the next round of negotiations.

Most recent KPI 15 results (number of programmes achieving each score, comparison between 2020/21 and 2021/22):

How have programme scores changed since last year?:


How many programmes reported: 53

The highest scoring programmes for this KPI in 2021/22 were:

Annual results:

For KPI 15, programmes report the likelihood of transformational change based on available evidence, on a scale from 1 - 5. For this reason, the results cannot be reported cumulatively. Instead we present the distribution of programmes across each score category per year.

In previous years this indicator used a scale from 0 - 4. However, the data model used in our results collation software made it difficult to distinguish between programmes reporting a score of 0 (a true 0) and programmes not reporting in any given year. At the same time, we have improved the definitions of each category, making it easier for reporting teams to score their programmes, while removing ambiguity from data processing steps.
